summary.seg: This manuscript, probably copied in the first half of the 16th century, contains a miscellany of Canon law and other religious and linguistic texts in Greek. The majority of the content is drawn from collections of canon law and brief texts and excerpts on miscellaneous religious questions, mainly of patristic origin but occasionally the work of later Byzantine clerics. There are also some lexicographical texts and a small portion of a grammatical work.

The most recent contents are a number of works of 15th-century origin written against the 1438 Union of Florence between the eastern and western churches. These include works by Markos Eugenikos (c. 1392-c. 1445), leader of opposition to the Union, a joint decree of 1443 by the three Patriarchs of Alexandria, Antioch and Jerusalem, and the decree of a synod held in Constantinople in 1484.

The manuscript is a composite of two parts, both produced in the same period and in a similar style, but by different hands and with distinct sequences of quire signatures, indicating that they were originally separate projects. It retains a Greek binding in the Byzantine style.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers 1-561 in Arabic numerals, in pencil, recto, upper right.
supportDesc.condition: Damage to the upper edge of ff. 1-95 has been repaired with paper strips. There is extensive pest damage throughout, some of it more recent than these repairs. This has been repaired with Japanese paper. There is extensive and severe water staining, which has led to serious fading of text in the upper part of the folios through much of the manuscript. There are occasional small tears from the edges of folios and areas of dirt.

binding.p: Textblock cut to the size of the boards.
Four sewing stations prepared with v-notches. Sewing is on double-cords with a Z-twist sewing thread.
Both endbands have broken threads. Greek-style compound endbands. Primary wound endband around a cord core, with secondary chevron in blue and yellow with a third thin crowning cord.
There are two cloth spine linings, one extending up to one third of the board and one up to two thirds of the board. The endband tiedowns pass through these patches of cloth.
Laid paper integral endleaves made of one pastedown only.
Board attachment is the cord sewing supports laced into the board. Small channels are visible on the outside face of the boards in which the supports lay.
Wooden boards. The boards have grooved edges and the outer spine edges are shaped to form a round that meets the textblock at the shoulder.

Full covering of dark brown tanned skin. Decoration uses blind tooling with intaglio hand-tools and fillets. Quintuple fillet border with two diagonals made of triple fillets. Floral hand-tool on the four corners of the outer border and in the middle, as well as in the diagonal intersection. Intaglio tooling of a double-headed eagle in the centre of the four panels created by the two intersecting diagonals. Fleur-de-lys tools surround the double-headed eagles (ten flowers in total). Both boards have the same decoration pattern.
There are two metal alloy foredge catch pins and the remains of three plaited straps on the right inner board.

accMat.p: A small fragment of a lost folio is housed along with the manuscript. This appears to belong to a folio preceding the present f. 1r, being copied by the same hand and apparently belonging to the same text.
Slips of paper with notes regarding discontinuous content are inserted loose between some folios.

history.provenance: Owned by C. J. Cummings Cummings, C. J. of Volos.
history.acquisition: Bought by Cambridge University Library from Cummings in 1892 through H. C. Rae Rae, H. C. of Liverpool.

collation.p: This part consists of 29 quires, of which eight are ternia and the rest are quaternia. The signatures suggest that a further two quires have been lost, probably at the beginning of the manuscript and/or after Quire 6.

handNote.p: ff. 1r-35v, 44r-49r, 63v, line 14-f. 108v, line 8, 109r-207v were copied by Hand A in mixed minuscule script, slanting slightly to the right, in brown ink, with modest variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are round and mute iota is subscript. There is decorative use of the double dot and accentuation of all nomina sacra. Accents are sometimes joined to letters, breathings and nomina sacra strokes.
The modern eta, modern nu, loop epsilon and sigma telikon are in use.
Punctuation used includes the lower, middle and upper points and full stop.
Headings are written in the same style in red ink.
ff. 36r-43v, 50r-63v, line 13 were copied by Hand B in mixed minuscule script, slanting slightly to the right, in brown ink, with modest variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear only at the end of lines. Breathings are round and mute iota is subscript. Use of the double dot is functional only. A single dot sometimes appears on iota. There is accentuation of all nomina sacra. Accents are sometimes joined to letters, breathings and nomina sacra strokes.
The modern nu and small x-shaped kappa are in use.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, middle comma and full stop.
f. 108v, lines 9-15 were copied by Hand C in mixed minuscule script with variable slant, in brown ink, with modest variation in letter size.
Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are round. Accents are sometimes joined to letters and abbreviations.
The modern eta , modern nu, small x-shaped kappa and sigma telikon are in use.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points and lower and middle commas.

decoDesc.decoNote: Sections and important words begin with normal or slightly enlarged letters in red ink.

history.origin: This part was probably copied in the first half of the 16th century, as indicated by the watermarks. This is consistent with the style of script.

collation.p: This part consists of 45 quires, all quaternia. The signatures suggest that a further nine quires have been lost between Quires 47 and 48 (ff. 351 and 352).

handNote.p: ff. 208r-561v were copied by Hand D in mixed minuscule script, slanting slightly to the right, in brown ink, with modest variation in letter size.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings appear throughout the line. Breathings are round and mute iota is subscript or absent. A single dot often appears above iota and upsilon. There is accentuation of all nomina sacra. Accents are sometimes joined to letters, breathings, abbreviations and nomina sacra strokes.
The modern eta, modern nu, small x-shaped kappa, loop epsilon and sigma telikon are in use.
Punctuation used includes the middle and upper points, middle comma and full stop.

decoDesc.decoNote: Sections and important words begin with normal or slightly enlarged letters in red ink.

history.origin: This part was probably copied in the first half of the 16th century, as indicated by the watermarks. This is consistent with the style of script.
